In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims March as Women's History Month, honoring the accomplishments of women and their role in shaping the nation's history. He highlights the progress women have made in various fields, such as the workforce, education, entrepreneurship, and government. The article commemorates the 100th anniversary of International Women's Day and acknowledges the ongoing struggle for gender equality. The administration's foreign policy includes empowering women globally and integrating gender considerations in diplomatic efforts. In the United States, efforts are being made to protect women's rights, address violence against women, support female entrepreneurs, and promote workplace flexibility and equal pay. The administration also aims to invest in education and expand opportunities for women and girls in STEM fields. The article concludes by calling on Americans to celebrate Women's History Month and International Women's Day, and to learn more about the contributions of women throughout history.